  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "The main reason is that RNNs suffer from the vanishing gradient problem since long-term information must sequentially travel through all RNN units before generating results.",
    "Thus, such information will likely vanish by being multiplied many times by small values.",
    "RNN-like networks, such as LSTM and GRU, consider this problem, but their more complex architectures still present sequential paths from older past units until the final one.",
    "For example, mHealth applications daily assess different multifeature longitudinal data of their users, which generate multi-longitudinal sequences of health data (Wac 2016).",
    "In five years, the longitudinal data sequence will have about 1825 timesteps."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "For example, mHealth applications daily assess different multifeature longitudinal data of their users, which generate multi-longitudinal sequences of health data (Wac 2016)."
  ]
}